\chapter{IMPLEMENTATION \& RESULTS}\label{implementation-results}

\section{Software Code
Implementation}\label{software-code-implementation}

\begin{quote}
The system implementation consists of core code blocks across the
robotic hand, backend, and frontend.
\end{quote}

\subsection{MediaPipe Landmark Mimicry and
Filter}\label{mediapipe-landmark-mimicry-and-filter}

\begin{quote}
The MediaPipe tracker module hand\_memic.py runs a continuous video
frame processing loop. The landmarks are processed to compute normalized
finger extension ratios, which are mapped to servo
angles:\includegraphics[width=6.36736in,height=2.28681in]{./media/image49.png}

These raw ratios are converted to servo command angles using per-finger
linear interpolation ranges:

\emph{A} = clamp \textsuperscript{\uline{\emph{Ri - Ri,}min}} \emph{$\times$} 100
+ 50\emph{,} 50\emph{,} 150
(16)\includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.12153in,keepaspectratio]{./media/image49.png}

\emph{Ri,}max \emph{- Ri,}min
\end{quote}

\subsection{Distance Filtering and Stability
Control}\label{distance-filtering-and-stability-control}

\begin{quote}
The distance reading obtained from the HC-SR04 palm sensor is noisy. We
implement the

DistanceFilter
class:\includegraphics[width=6.36736in,height=3.16181in]{./media/image49.png}

\includegraphics[width=5.00094in,height=6.84125in]{./media/image61.jpg}

Fig. 16: Signal Flow: Circular Median Filter and Stability Verification
Pipeline
\end{quote}

\subsection{Autonomous Finite State
Machine}\label{autonomous-finite-state-machine}

\begin{quote}
The autonomous controller runs an active loop running at 50 Hz. The
state transitions are managed via the AutoState enumeration:

\includegraphics[width=4.92708in,height=9.875in]{./media/image57.png}

Fig. 17: State Machine Pipeline: Ultrasonic Detection to Final Robotic
Grasp Action
\end{quote}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  READY: The sensor detects an object at a stable distance (e.g., 6.5
  cm). The system queries the Motion Library to retrieve the matching
  trajectory.
\item
  GRABBING: Executes time-based playback of the trajectory, writing
  servo command bytes "Aa1,a2,a3,a4,a5\emph{\textbackslash{}}n" to the
  serial port.
\item
  HOLDING: The hand holds the object. A separate daemon thread triggers
  OCR pro-cessing to identify the label.
\item
  RELEASING: Once the OCR resolves and backend dispatch signals
  completion, the hand opens all fingers and releases the package,
  pausing 2 seconds before re-entering detection.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Asynchronous OCR Concurrency
Timeline}\label{asynchronous-ocr-concurrency-timeline}

\begin{quote}
OCR execution takes 1.8 seconds on average. If performed in the main
control loop, it would cause the state machine to freeze. We offload the
execution to a daemon thread:
\end{quote}

\includegraphics[width=4.55729in,height=4.20729in]{./media/image62.jpg}

\begin{quote}
Fig. 18: Concurrency Timeline: Main Control Loop and Asynchronous VLM
Daemon Thread
\end{quote}

